Helm is the official package manager for Kubernetes that automates the deployment, scaling, and management of complex containerized 
applications. It operates by bundling Kubernetes manifests (like deployments, services, and ingresses) into a single, reusable package 
called a Helm Chart.

Core Concepts of Helm
Understanding Helm requires mastering three fundamental building blocks:

Chart: A blueprint package containing all the YAML templates needed to build a Kubernetes application.
Values: A values.yaml file containing configuration parameters that inject custom data into the Chart templates.
Release: A specific, running instance of a Chart deployed inside your Kubernetes cluster.

Helm Architecture (Helm v3)Helm v3 uses a client-only architecture that interacts directly with the Kubernetes API Server.
No Server Component: Helm v3 completely removed Tiller (the server component from Helm v2) to strictly enforce Kubernetes Role-Based 
Access Control (RBAC) security permissions.
Release Secrets: Helm stores release metadata directly inside the cluster as Kubernetes Secrets within the target namespace.
Chart Repositories: Charts are hosted and shared via HTTP servers or OCI registries like Docker Hub, GitHub Packages, or Artifact Hub.

Common Helm Commands
Managing applications with Helm relies on a few concise lifecycle commands:
helm repo add: Registers a remote chart repository to your local system.
helm search repo: Searches your added repositories for available charts.
helm install: Deploys a chart to your cluster, creating a new release.
helm upgrade: Updates an existing release with new configuration values or chart versions.
helm rollback: Reverts a failed deployment to a previous successful release revision.
helm uninstall: Deletes a release and all of its associated Kubernetes resources.

Why Use Helm?

Helm solves several structural challenges when scaling applications in production:
Template Reusability: Write one deployment manifest and use variables to deploy it across dev, staging, and production environments.
Dependency Management: Charts can declare dependencies on other charts (e.g., an app chart requiring a PostgreSQL chart to run first).
Atomic Rollbacks: If an upgrade fails, a single command completely reverts the cluster state cleanly.
Standardized Sharing: Simplifies installing complex third-party tools like Prometheus, cert-manager, or NGINX Ingress with a single
command.
